---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="API Access Management — Tuva Ødegård" lang="en">
  <article>
    <header class="project-header">
      <div class="meta">
        <span class="year">2025</span>
        <span class="badge">Case study</span>
      </div>
      <h1>API Access Management</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Redesigning a complex access control interface to make granular API
        permissions faster and less error-prone.
      </p>
      <ul class="tags">
        <li>UX Design</li>
        <li>Frontend</li>
        <li>Internal tooling</li>
        <li>Fintech</li>
      </ul>
    </header>

    <div class="content">
      <section>
        <h2>Background</h2>
        <p>
          This work is part of an internal tool for managing API access
          for internal and external clients. It gives an overview of clients and their
          assigned APIs, a changelog of changes per client, and a few other
          administrative functions.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>The problem</h2>
        <p>
          One of the features on this tool is the ability to manage which APIs a
          client has access to. The existing interface for this used a dual-panel
          "add/remove" pattern. While functional, it had several
          issues: raw UUIDs were visible to users, the list was unordered and
          ungrouped, and — critically — granular access control was a separate
          two-step process. Users had to add an API, save, navigate back to the
          overview, find the entry they just added, and only then configure
          which specific endpoints to allow.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}images/api/api-access-wireframe.png`}
            alt="Wireframe of the original dual-panel interface for adding and removing API access"
          />
        </figure>
        <p><em>This is an internal project, so actual screenshots are not available. The wireframes shown here are recreated to illustrate the concept — the original Figma designs and final implementation were both done by me.</em></p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Process</h2>
        <p>
          I started by talking to the people who used the system regularly to
          understand where the friction actually was. One thing that came up: removing
          access was rare. The interface was built around adding and removing as
          equally common actions, but in practice bulk removal almost never happened.
          That changed how I thought about the solution. From there I sketched out
          alternatives in Figma, focusing on collapsing the two-step add flow into one
          and moving removal out of the main path entirely.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>The solution</h2>
        <p>
          Adding access got a dedicated modal with inline granular controls —
          no more saving and navigating back to configure endpoints. Removing was
          moved to a three-dot menu on each individual access card, keeping it
          accessible without cluttering the primary flow.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}images/api/popover-wireframe.png`}
            alt="Wireframe of the new Add access popover with inline granular endpoint selection"
          />
        </figure>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Outcome</h2>
        <p>
          After launch, a product lead who uses the system regularly reached out
          unprompted with this feedback (translated from Norwegian):
        </p>
        <blockquote>
          "Managing API access for clients has received a real lift and become
          much easier — and prettier. Both adding and removing access. Really
          great work."
        </blockquote>
        <p>
          Worth noting: both adding <em>and</em> removing were called out as
          improved, even though removing was deliberately moved out of the main
          flow. That felt like a good signal that the restructuring had worked.
        </p>
        <p>
          This was also one of my first projects on this team. Getting up to
          speed on an unfamiliar system quickly enough to identify a real
          problem and ship a solution was a useful reminder that being new
          somewhere doesn't mean waiting before contributing.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  article {
    max-width: 680px;
  }

  .project-header {
    margin-bottom: 4rem;
    padding-bottom: 2.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }

  .meta {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .year {
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
  }

  .badge {
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--accent);
    border: 1px solid var(--accent);
    padding: 0.15rem 0.5rem;
    border-radius: 2px;
  }

  h1 {
    font-size: 2rem;
    font-weight: 400;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.2;
  }

  .lead {
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .tags {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.4rem;
    list-style: none;
  }

  .tags li {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    background: #e4e8ef;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    border-radius: 2px;
  }

  .content {
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .content section {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }

  .content h2 {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
  }

  .content p {
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .content p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .content em {
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .content blockquote {
    border-left: 2px solid var(--accent);
    margin: 1.25rem 0;
    padding: 0.25rem 0 0.25rem 1.25rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .content figure {
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
  }

  .content figure img {
    width: 100%;
    border-radius: 4px;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    display: block;
  }
</style>
